title: For Sale:  LNIB Smith and Wesson M&P 9mm with Apex Tactical USB and RAM
postcontent:
For sale is an immaculate Smith & Wesson M&P 9mm. It does not even have a full box of ammo through it. It has everything that originally came with the firearm, which includes the box, two 17-round magazines, three backstraps to adjust the size of the grip for your specific comfort, a lock, and all original paperwork. This one is a full size frame with a 4.25" barrel.

The M&P is a solid firearm for personal and home defense and smooth to shoot. The one criticism often heard is about the mushiness of the trigger, especially on reset. To correct that, this firearm already has Apex's Universal Striker Block and also it's Reset Assist Mechanism (RAM). The trigger reset is now both tactile and audible for those lightning double taps.

I'm asking $5755 OBO for this firearm. I saw a brand new one just last week at a local dealer but just for the stock model, their price is much higher than my price, even before tax. I won't call mine new because that would be a lie; but, the only difference is a few extra rounds fired. Look closely at the pictures though, and you will see that the slide has no holster wear. On top there is a little rubbing but nothing else, which supports that only a few rounds have been fired through this firearm.

I would consider trades for firearms that are of different manufacturers so that I can diversify.  Any sales or trades would require two forms of ID to include your driver's license and either your voter registration card or concealed permit and willingness to complete a simple bill of sale.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Bushmaster Varminter Upper
location: Raleigh/Garner, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: I don't necessarily need to sell it, but I'm putting my Bushmaster Varminter upper on the market. I don't shoot it nearly as often as I'd like, and I'd prefer somebody else get the chance to actually shoot and maybe do some hunting with it. I've put around 600 rounds through it. That is not really a lot of wear, and it is in great condition. Other than the few times I've shot it, it pretty much just sits in the rifle case. It has a 24" bull barrel with a 1 in 9" twist. While that is optimum for lighter varmint rounds, it will shoot 75 grain match rounds at 500 yards all day long, as long as the shooter can use the rifle correctly. The bipod is not included. I'll include the Millett 4-16 power scope with illuminated mil-dot reticle for a total of $1400. The scope is very clear, and has only been used to shoot once. If you don't agree with the price, just make an offer. The least I can say is no. I'll also consider trades for firearms and/or ammo. I can also sell some 5.56 ammo for extra cash. Prefer to sell local, but will ship with cost added to price.

title: For Sale:  Compensator with Muzzle Coupling for MarkII 10" Bull BBL
postcontent:
One left!  I have what I call a "high volume compensator" paired with a muzzle coupling for a Ruger MarkII with a 10" Bull Bbl. The compensator is an empty tube that allows the gas to expand and cool, then to vent upwards through ports in the end of the tube. This reduces felt recoil and muzzle rise to keep you on target.  They are threaded 1/2x20.  There is a set screw on the rear bushing that lets you rotate the tube to position the vents upward.
The muzzle coupling allows you to use the threaded compensators (or other threaded accessories) without having a threaded barrel.  The coupling fits over the end of the barrel with a slot for the front site.  Then, two split rings can be tightened up against the rear of the front site to lock the coupling in place and providing a 1/2x20 thread for accessories.
All parts are blued steel.  
This listing is for a 5" compensator and a muzzle coupling for a Ruger MarkII with a 10" Bull Target bbl.  This bbl is a round, slightly tapered bbl.  It is not for a slab-side bull bbl.
The gun shown is not included.  This listing is for the muzzle-coupling, compensator and thread protector only.  
The first two I had posted sold within 24 hours of posting.  Don't wait.  $100.

title: For Sale:  Compensators with Muzzle Coupling for Ruger 10/22
postcontent:
I have a few pairs of what I call "high volume compensators" paired with muzzle couplings for specific Ruger models. The compensators are empty tubes that allow the gas to expand and cool, then to vent upwards through ports in the end of the tube. This reduces felt recoil and muzzle rise to keep you on target.  They are threaded 1/2x20.  There is a set screw on the rear bushing that lets you rotate the tube to position the vents upward.
The muzzle couplings allow you to use these threaded compensators (or other threaded accessories) without having threaded barrels.  The couplings fit over the end of the barrel with a slot for the front site.  Then, two split rings can be tightened up against the rear of the front site to lock the coupling in place and providing a 1/2x20 thread for accessories.
All parts are blued steel.  
This listing is for a 6" compensator with muzzle coupling for a Ruger 10/22 rifle, std bbl., a threaded flash suppressor and a thread protector. $100.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mateba Autorevolver
postcontent:
Mateba Sportiva Grifone autorevolver, 8 Inch barrel.  Excellent condition, beautiful bluing and grips.  Out of production for several years, real collector's item!  When they come up on gunbroker, they sell for $4,000 plus!  

The Mateba Model 6 uses the recoil from firing to rotate the cylinder and cock the hammer, unlike conventional revolvers, which depend on the user physically pulling the trigger and/or cocking the hammer to actuate the weapon's mechanism of operation.
The Mateba Autorevolver's barrel alignment is different from most other revolvers. The barrel is aligned with the bottom of the cylinder instead of the top. This lowers the bore axis (line of the barrel) which directs the recoil in line with the shooter's hand thereby reducing the twisting motion or muzzle flip of normal revolvers. The gun's entire upper assembly (barrel, cylinder and frame) are mounted on rails on the lower frame, which houses the trigger, hammer, and grip, and recoils 1/2 of an inch, or 12.7mm, on firing. The rearward motion of the upper assembly cocks the hammer, and the cylinder is rotated on the forward stroke.

I'm busy during the day but you can text me at 573-864-7323 if you're interested.  I will take any photos you want after I get home from work.

title: For Sale:  RPB Open Bolt M11-A1 .380.
postcontent:
Extremely rare Mac series semi auto pistol with a great history
The 380 caliber is the rarest of the already rare RPB series of pistols made in 1982

LITTLE HISTORY
RPB was on the verge of going under from finical problems. In the late 1970s Wayne Daniel purchased a large majority of the companies stock and started to produce semi-auto versions of the M11-A1. By removing the collapsible stock and the ability to fire Full-Auto, the open bolt SM11-A1 became a Title 1 pistol and could be purchased by anyone.

These new semi versions of the M11 sold like hot cakes until the BATF intervened in 1982 because they felt these open bolt semi-auto copies could be converted to Full-Auto to easily. Because of this all open-bolt pistol produced after 1982 are considered Machine Guns and this is why we don’t see semi-auto open bolt guns any more.

Luckily for owners of these semi-auto pistols all guns not modified on or produced before the ruling were grand fathered and not considered machine guns.

Unfortunately this ruling by the BATF hurt RPB financially and brought unwanted legal attention so Wayne Daniel dissolved the company in April 1982.

The RPB SM11-A1 is chambered in .380 ACP & uses steel magazines in either 16 or 32 round capacities. Unlike most M-11s it has no collapsible stock that extends from the butt of the weapon and only fires in semi-auto. It does use the open bolt method of operation & the end of the barrel is threaded to accept a silencer or other barrel accessory. Compared to other M-11s the RPB guns are generally of a higher quality.

The RPB SM11-A1s is rare because they are the last of the legal open-bolt semi-auto pistols. Because of this they command a good deal for a Title 1 pistol on the open market because MAC collectors are always on the look out for them.


Comes with fake extension and strap
One 16 round and two 32 round magazines
In excellent condition

Very cool and a great piece for any collection

Will need to see a Colorado DL/CHP/CCW
Face to Face

title: For Sale:  THIS IS THE REAL DEAL NOT THE COPIES OTHER ARE PAWNING OFF ON YOU.
postcontent:
Interdynamic KG-9 TEC9 "assault" pistol 
The TEC-9 design was started in Sweden, when the Interdynamic AB company of Stockholm developed a relatively simple submachine gun. Since Sweden was a poor market for such product, a subsidiary company Interdynamic was established in Miami (Florida, USA), to market Interdynamic guns in USA. As the full-automatic weapons market in USA is very restrictive, the basic submachine gun was converted in semi-automatic only variant, apparently suitable for civilian US market. This semi-automatic pistol, like its submachine gun predecessor, was a simple blowback design, firing from the open bolt. It was designated Interdynamic KG-9. But, sooner than later, US Bureau of  Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms (BATF) found that this semiautomatic pistol can be easily converted back to full automatic, and restricted it manufacture. Interdynamic redesigned the KG-9 into "closed bolt" design by adding the separate striker, and designated it KG-99. About the same time (mid-1980s) the Interdynamic of USA turned into Intratec Firearms, Inc, based in the same city of Miami (Florida). Intratec initially  produced the KG-99 under the designation of  TEC-9, but about 1989 renamed it into DC-9. With the introduction of the infamous US Assault Weapons Ban in 1994 the Intratec pistols were prohibited for manufacture (but not for ownership, if made before the ban) AND THIS ONE WAS MADE AND PURCHASED BEFORE THE BAN. Original owner with original booklet.
